4. KINGDOM OF THE PLANET OF THE APES
In that order.

author: @TyroneHollins-gg2gd
text:
In addition to the questionable establishment of apes as human proxy in these films we must contend with the truly troubling comparative dynamic of human-to-ape to slaver-to-slave. Even after the United States declared emancipation for all humans, Southern states negotiated the horrific â€œ3/5sâ€ compromise, a legislative writ asserting an enforceable ratio of measurable humanity. Whites rate 5 out of 5, blacks rate 3. White America is (and always will be) poisoned by this legacy of thought. Are these films asserting that the human-to-ape is comparable to our human-to-human equations? Perhaps if we decide that indeed, all Godâ€™s creatures are equal, we easily solve this equation. It is nevertheless troubling to watch Conquest of the Planet of the Apes and have to accept that, in this film, humans are white slave owners, and apes are black slaves. I donâ€™t think a biblical platitude solves this particular math.

(American black slavery is of course not the sole instance of human trafficking, but these are American films about American societies, and given that the Union as it stands today was mapped in blood from a war entirely motivated by the inability of Southern states to let go their slaves, itâ€™s fair to read them in these terms.)

author: @TyroneHollins-gg2gd
text:
The Ape training centers were inspired by real life training centers for black slaves. The brutality that black America has endured besides the systematic eradication of thier language, culture, tradition, religion, everything that makes us unique.
Caesar!Conquest of the Planet of the ApesJ Lee ThompsonMatt ReevesRacism

The Planet of the Apes franchise was constructed on the backs of two cheery thematic tortoises:

bigotry may be unsolvable,
and humanity will always devolve into chaos.
This is a deeply nihilistic franchise, all the way through Matt Reevesâ€™ brutal contemporary reimagining. The original films, however, have a hardness to them that modern film canâ€™t quite appropriate: their budgets and limited toolset forced on them a minimalist claustrophobia that the expansive new films canâ€™t touch. Conquest of the Planet of the Apes, as Rupert Giles might say, makes the subtext text. By foregrounding race and violence in a contemporary American city, Conquest is perhaps the most vicious and socially relevant of them all.

Starting with the first film, the franchise deliberately establishes uneasy parallels to racial tensions in Western countries. Planet of the Apes was created in the raging heart of the 1960s civil rights movement, and was unafraid to portray via metaphor what literal dramatization would not yet touch: the inevitable cycles of cruelty and enslavement that a modicum of genetic difference can inspire. When we first discover the planet of the apes after the humans of our earth have fallen, human remnants have somehow devolved into unclothed mutes. Apes round them up and sell them at auction. They are animals. In the original film, apes are loosely correlated to white slave-owners in pre-Civil War America, and the feral humans the black slaves. As with human society, apes are not unanimously accepting of slavery and actively protest it.

author: @RcMx2050
text: Is Mae the descendant of Astronaut George Taylor or Astronaut Brent, somehow traveling through time to help her father?    Or is she the descendant of Astronaut Leo Davidson (from the movie released in 2001), traveling back through time to try to stop Proximus Caesar from making the world like that to which Leo returned?   Or is she simply from a tribe of humans that shared a DNA strain making them immune from the virus?    If she'd merely been awakened from a cryopreservation pod, she could conceivably become infected at any time and the plot could become less interesting, indeed.   At any rate, perhaps we can all agree that our being held in suspense about Mae, like we are, is excellent marketing, especially for the 10th movie in a 55+ year old movie franchise?   :-)

text: Does anyone else find the titles of the new Planet of the Apes movies a bit clunky? Take 'Kingdom of the Planet of the Apes'â€”it's just too long with unnecessary repetitions. Why not just 'Kingdom of the Apes'? Itâ€™s shorter, catchier, and reduces the cognitive load of processing the title. The double prepositional phrases ('of the Planet' and 'of the Apes') make it overly complex. We all know it's part of the Apes franchise, so why make the title so cumbersome and less fluid? They could definitely streamline these titles to make them more appealing and memorable.

author: @ridiqulos
text: I watched the reboot in the theaters, and I loved them all but felt that Dawn and War never peaked as good as Rise.  I'm re-watching them all and I now have such a fond appreciation for Dawn.  Each movie focused on telling a different story on how apes became the prominent species on the planet.  They drilled down on Caesars development, from this happy cute baby to a stoic tortured empathetic leader.  The first time I watched dawn I felt like, where is James Franco, like what end up happening to him?  That's the point, the story isn't about Caesars father, it's about Caesar, and that was just one point of his life, the first 15 years that gave him a perspective towards humans that no other ape can ever experience.  Hope Kingdom doesn't disappoint!

author: @arianedupont8958
text:
I don't understand all those "anti-woke" comments.
Do you realize that around 50 % of the world's population is woman?
Throughout history they have always been queen, prestresses, warriors, knights, and goddesses in every mythologie.
They maybe have been erased from history in Europe, because some dudes in the 13 century decided they would rule the world alone and reduce them in slavery, but they are still 50 % of the population and very well occupying some major roles in society.
A movie starring a woman as a principal character is just as logical as a movie starring a man.
It's not "woke"
Now, in the US, only about 10 % of the population is black, so having every American movie staring a black guy is highly political.
And it's even more political when they decide to turn black some real historical figures that have never been black, to impose their Afrocentrism... like in Bridgerton (a real queen of England is voluntarily turned into a black woman) or in Cleopatra (historically it's proved and reproved that she was not)... and so on.
This is "woke" or to be more exact, this is a political weapon.

author: @WhatsaTsurt
text:
Can we all agree, that the reboot of this franchise has to be one of the best reboots of any franchise? Right up there with each new generation of James Bond and Godzilla movies.

Most other reboots fail to capture the actual essence of the originals, or it just falls flat. But Planet of the Apes has done such a great job with it. Not rushing the movies. But taking their time with each movie. One of the few franchises that I am regularly excited for and am willing to wait however long it takes.

author: @kennethsatria6607
text:
I really like how the antagonist seems to also have full knowledge and a fascination of how powerful and advanced humanity was in the past, and that he could be able to surpass them in making his kingdom greater much like ancient civilizations and tyrants in the past want to outdo their predecessors and be immortalized in history.

The only conflicting thing here is likely his cruelty towards humans and apes that defy him, but that doesn't come from any inner savagery, or delusion of divine right or religeon like most villains in the franchise, he just doesn't care about present day humanity and doesn't tolerate rebellious thinking because he has dreams of greatness.

That really makes him out as a more intelligent and cunning antagonist.
My interest is really hooked when he says that he/they "will learn" in such an enthusiastic way.

author: @SnowyGolem
text:
Ok I get that AI is controlling the narrative here, but hopefully somebody else reads this comment:

This trailer looks bad.
the voice actor for the orangutan couldn't sound more like a human.

the animation for the apes looks weird in some scenes.

a young human CANNOT outrun a gorilla.

and maybe this is just me, but I didn't recognize any of the characters from the originals.

I loved the first movies of this franchise, but this one does not look like it's going to be as good as the "AI generative comments" are making it out to be.

These movies are good because you're taking the high intelligence of an augmented ape with the strength of a normal ape, and pitting it against the numbers and resources of humans.

I can't imagine changing that recipe will increase the watchability of these movies.

author: @patricktilton5377
text:
As I've said before, since the reboot trilogy never included a Nuclear War as the major element in the destruction of the human civilization, it cannot be a direct prequel to the 1968 original PLANET OF THE APES, since that was THE major element added to that film adaptation of Pierre Boulle's source novel. The original film established that sometime in the 28th Century an orangutan heralded as "the greatest ape of all, our Lawgiver" wrote the SACRED SCROLLS, in which he effectively re-wrote Ape History to such a point that any thought that there might have been a prior advanced civilization of Humans was erased. Yet, in the meantime, there were some apes -- such as the lineage leading up to Dr. Zaius -- who were (as Taylor called Zaius) "the Guardian of the Terrible Secret" and made sure that any Human displaying any signs of being able to Write or to Speak would be "dissected" and then "killed" -- in that order.
The RISE-DAWN-WAR trilogy of films, then, is a reboot of the basic concept, but cannot be a direct prequel to the Classic POTA film (and its sequels/prequels BENEATH, ESCAPE, CONQUEST, and BATTLE.
Having said all that, though, I must say that I thoroughly enjoyed the reboot trilogy, and this KINGDOM looks to be absolutely amazing. I don't want to get my hopes up -- the Burton "Re-Imagining" film having missed the mark so badly -- but it's hard not to, seeing this trailer.

author: @snapecv04
text:
There hasn't been a decent planet of the apes since 1968 and based on how simple and slowly the words are delivered in the exposition/narration here I am not optimistic. To be frank the central conflict in this film looks identical to the last 2 movies in the trilogy. The 2011 film was somewhat interesting but the sequels were identical in their themes "human bad but also human good and ape good but also ape bad" pure surface level about our morphology not defining what it is to be considered sentient and moral.

The 1968 film however was a master peace. Every moment in the film, every piece of dialog touches on an aspect of society be it intraspecies conflict, tribalism, hierarchy, anthropology, evolution, religion, secularism, biology, class, civilisation, race, animal welfare all wrapped up in a harrowing twist. The movie is also very poetic, an example is the main characters motivations to meet something greater than man and he gets his wish alright however man is now primitive and dominated by a civilised species of ape who demonstrate all the same virtues and vices as humans from the main characters time. Dr Seuss also an extremely fascinating character, a very dogmatic kind of religious clergyman in the beginning but as the movie progresses its revealed he knows a lot more about human history than he omits. <spoiler> As its revealed humanity has destroyed itself I get the feeling Dr Seuss not only knew of their self-annihilation but is actively trying to avoid such a fate for apes, as its shown he can shutdown an area of scientific study (anthro/archaeology) and prevent technological progress. My suspicion is Dr Seuss knows exactly how humans killed themselves (ICBM's) hence his absolute condemnation of the notion of flight as shown when the main character makes a paper airplane. Dr Seuss hatred for the main character is initially interpreted as a reaction to a specieal equal to apes however this is likely not attributed to a Copernican loss of importance but rather Dr Seuss knows this is the civilisation destroyer before him. In a strange way the ending flips the antagonist and the protagonist; the antagonist actually safeguarding ape kind and the protagonist belonging to a people that destroyed themselves, their civilisation and as we can seen somewhat destroyed the earths ecosystem.

I will still watch Kingdom but I'm 100% sure its never going to come even close to the original 1968 .

author: @alersonbernardo
text: This isn't Cornelius; he's probably a direct descendant of Caesar, judging by the resemblance. If the movie is set 300 years in the future, we can consider the following calculation: A chimpanzee can live around 40 or 50 years. They reach adulthood around 12 years old. Caesar became a father around that age and had two sons. The older one, "Blue Eyes," was killed by the Colonel, leaving Cornelius as the only survivor after the war. So, Noah must be the twenty-fifth generation counting from Caesar, who was the first. The calculation is as follows: take 300 years and divide by 12 (considering adulthood and sexual maturity), which results in 300/12 = 25.

author: @Justmyhandle
text:
As much as I'll miss Andy Serkis' performance as Caesar (He may appear in flashbacks or some kind of vision to his son), I absolutely LOVE the premise of a new trilogy exploring how the next generations of apes react to his example and what different factions take away from his legacy as they conflict over what the best way is to shape the future.

Caesar's son will likely be the main protagonist going forward (I assume that girl is the young child from the last film grown up), but this trailer (and the 1968 original, if this new canon sets it up) seems to imply that his campaign against human slavery will fail. "No one can stop the reign" doesn't give a very optomistic tone for the surviving humans.

The best they can hope for now is freedom, security, and perhaps independence under a benevolent ape ruler to start their own society. I do hope this rebooted continuity doesn't reverse that paradigm in the end with humans somehow curing the effects of the virus, regaining their higher intellect, and once again trying to reclaim the Earth. That'd be such a cop-out.

Not every story needs to have a happy ending for us. Moreover, it'd undermine the themes of this franchise. The Planet of the Apes films were always interpretable as a cautionary tale about humanity authoring its own downfall. The apes could always be perceived as a vehicle to contemplate how a new dominant species might learn from and/or emulate us.

text: It's incredible how far this series has gone. We saw the very origins in the first film, the post apocalyptic world in the next, the last remnants of humanity turning feral from the virus after that, and now we're seeing a complete reversal: apes rule the world and humans are feral creatures hunted for sport. This is a series that has seen its entire world shift into a completely different form, and it's really amazing to see.

author: @Quetzalcoatl_Feathered_Serpent
text:
There has always been a tragedy to Planet of the Apes.

Humanity and Apes are all related yet they never except in brief isolated situations been able to work alongside each other or lived together united.

The Strengths and Flaws of humanity also are the same in the apes. Showing that both are the same even if they look different at first. They have the same desires, the same ideals, good intentions, bad intentions, peace, and power.

Ape nature is apparently the same as Human Nature and this makes sense if you study human evolution.

If the series continues its timeslips we likely will see future apes continue to resemble humanity even more as they continue the drive of civilization. To the point they will begin to resemble the apes from both the original planet of the apes and the 2001 version.
